T1  - Lottery-Related Anomalies: The Role of Reference-Dependent Preferences
AU  - An, Li
AU  - Wang, Huijun
AU  - Wang, Jian
AU  - Yu, Jianfeng
Y1  - 2019/07/31
PY  - 2019
DA  - 2020/01/01
N1  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3205
DO  - 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3205
T2  - Management Science
JF  - Management Science
JO  - Management Science
SP  - 473
EP  - 501
VL  - 66
IS  - 1
PB  - INFORMS
N2  - Previous empirical studies find that lottery-like stocks significantly underperform their non-lottery-like counterparts. Using five different measures of the lottery features in the literature, we document that the anomalies associated with these measures are state dependent: the evidence supporting these anomalies is strong and robust among stocks where investors have lost money, whereas among stocks where investors have gained profits, the evidence is either weak or even reversed. Several potential explanations for such empirical findings are examined, and we document support for the explanation based on reference-dependent preferences. Our results provide a unified framework to understand the lottery-related anomalies in the literature.This paper was accepted by Tyler Shumway, finance.
AB  - Previous empirical studies find that lottery-like stocks significantly underperform their non-lottery-like counterparts. Using five different measures of the lottery features in the literature, we document that the anomalies associated with these measures are state dependent: the evidence supporting these anomalies is strong and robust among stocks where investors have lost money, whereas among stocks where investors have gained profits, the evidence is either weak or even reversed. Several potential explanations for such empirical findings are examined, and we document support for the explanation based on reference-dependent preferences. Our results provide a unified framework to understand the lottery-related anomalies in the literature.This paper was accepted by Tyler Shumway, finance.
SN  - 0025-1909
M3  - doi: 10.1287/mnsc.2018.3205
UR  - https://doi.org/10.1287/mnsc.2018.3205
Y2  - 2024/03/29
